[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tricky cuz there\'s no exact right answer, but I know which direction to look. The current Midjourney meta taps into these three things, and when you use them all together, oh baby. To start, the best strategy is going to'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sound super simple. Add as much detail as you can to your prompt. Like I said, that might sound silly, but it\'s true. You need to think of these details as visual anchors. Let me show you what to'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'add. Up front, one of the first things in your prompt should be the style that you\'re hoping to see. How do you want your images to look? I\'m talking about like art style or medium here. If you want something realistic, maybe you want'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the medium of photography. A Vogue portrait photo shoot of Robert Pattinson. Super simple start, right? Pick a style, add it somewhere near the front of your prompt. Then you\'re going to tie that style into whatever you want'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to show up. This is going to be your subject and setting. Don\'t be afraid to flip those two around. You can start with the setting if you want. That will change the results. Here\'s a Vogue portrait photo shoot of Walter White in'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the back of a dirty RV camper versus a photo shoot of a dirty RV camper with Walter White in the back. If you\'re not happy with your results or you pictured something different, try swapping the'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subject and your setting. And hey, I actually have a new course to announce. If you want to learn how to create cool coloring books like this, I\'ve broken down everything you need to know in 29 efficient and fast lessons. It will barely take you an hour to finish this'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'course, and you\'re going to learn everything I did to create these books, including how to create consistent coloring pages like you see here. And because the landing page is barely set up for the next couple of weeks, you can'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have 15% off if you use this code here. FTP15 at the checkout, 15% off as an early access special thanks to you for your support. Another detail that makes a big'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'difference is the idea of distance. Vogue portrait photo shoot of a dirty RV camper with Walter White in the back. There is a mega city far in the distant back left of the frame. And if you look'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'closely, we do see something back here. There are two things that I want you to learn from that. You can ask for pretty specific things, and you can prompt way more naturally. Okay, let\'s move away'

[02:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from Heisenberg for now. Let me show you another detail that contributes to better images, the camera. Instead of a selfie of a group of teenagers in the early \'90s, you could add some camera control like a low angle fish eye lens'

[02:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'selfie of a group of teenagers. And look at those results. Aren\'t those so cool? You know, that low angle is always fun, but you could also try a drone or an aerial shot. So, you\'re covering the behavior of the camera in your prompt,'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but another detail you can add is the behavior of your subject. Maybe the pose that they\'re in. Low angle fish eye lens of teenagers, the teenagers have their hands pointing out at the camera. When'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re including behavior in your prompt, you\'re moving away from those static AI images. Like look at that picture. That\'s so cool. Maybe the fingers are a little weird, but you know, I I think that\'s not bad. Or even something like this, a Vogue candid'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'photo shoot of Robert Pattinson side profile portrait. A portrait is the camera angle I want, and side profile is the pose of the subject. You could even specify that he is looking to the right'

[03:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the frame. I don\'t know if your directional controls are going to work every time, but these are the type of details that you can consider adding. All of these details build up the meta, and there are two more that you should'

[03:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be triggering in your prompt. The first is material language, like literally the texture of what you see in the image. You can think of a super simple scale of smooth to rough. A smooth oil painting of a dog versus a rough oil painting of'

[03:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a dog. Don\'t forget about what you want the texture of the image to be. That texture applies to the design itself, like minimal versus ornate, even the material of the costume your character'

[04:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is wearing, silk versus denim. I\'m trying to give you some really simple ideas here, some really simple ends of the scale, and then you can prompt for anywhere you want on that scale. And sorry for harping on texture so much,'

[04:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but it even applies to the medium. A Vogue portrait photo shoot of Batman versus a Vogue portrait oil painting. I\'m using Vogue as the style, portrait as the camera, and then photo shoot'

[04:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'versus oil painting as the texture. You know, these are not ironclad rules. You really don\'t have to listen to me here. I\'m just trying to mention the types of things you can be thinking about as you\'re building out your prompt. And the last visual anchor you want to add is'

[04:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the mood or atmosphere of your image. Where should you put this in your prompt? At the end, maybe. Just remember that if Midjourney isn\'t listening to some of your words, try putting those words closer to the front of the prompt.'

[04:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Because what you say first is inherently more important, especially the longer your prompt grows. Like here, I added that he is happy to the end of the prompt, and it didn\'t really work, kind of. So, I [snorts] can take the idea of'

[05:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happy and put it at the front of the prompt, a happy Robert Pattinson Vogue inspired oil painting, and this works a lot better. But this is a good example of not being too rigid in your prompt. Because instead of happy, I left the'

[05:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mood at the end, and this time I said he is smiling. And that worked a lot better. Like, he is happy down here, no smile. He is smiling, smile. So, you can rearrange your prompt or find different'

[05:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ways of describing the look you\'re going for. I hope that makes sense. Either way, dictate the detail of your prompt by adding these six visual anchors. Style, distance, camera, behavior, material, and mood. And I apologize if'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you think I should have mentioned this earlier, but I think you should build out your prompt as much as you can, and then use the describe feature. Right now, you can click on your image and drag it below the prompt box, or you can'

[06:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right click on an image and you\'ll see describe right here. Clicking on that will let Midjourney write four prompts for you based on that picture. Now, the results of these will probably be pretty'

[06:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'similar to what you generated, but you can learn a lot of cool words from these prompts. Different ways of approaching your goal. Like I ran this picture through the describe feature, and I used Vogue as like a trigger word for all of'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this. But what does Vogue portrait really mean? Well, look at what the describe feature did. Which way would you rather prompt? I think it\'s okay for you to use these more powerful words as shortcuts, but you should be using the'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'describe feature so you can become aware of just what your words actually mean. A black and white photograph featuring a smiling Robert Pattinson. His head and upper body are visible with his face turned slightly to the right. His dark'

[06:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hair is wet and styled in a messy manner with water droplets on his skin. He has stubble on his face and is wearing a dark heavy coat with a large collar. His teeth are visible as he smiles. The'

[07:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'background is a simple blurred light tone. All of that to describe this picture. Isn\'t that fascinating? You don\'t need all of these words. You could say a happy Robert Pattinson Vogue'

[07:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inspired portrait photo shoot. But somewhere between the minimal and the maximum are these visual anchors here. I\'m telling you to aim for somewhere in the middle. Honestly, the details of your prompt are going to do a lot of the'

[07:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'heavy lifting, but when you combine those details with parameters, you\'re going to find a lot more success. And the parameters I\'m talking about are style raw, chaos, stylize, and the EXP parameter. And I promise that I don\'t'

[07:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think any of these parameters is more important than the rest. What I\'m really trying to say is that you want a combo. So, the first thing I would try in every prompt is running that prompt through style raw. You can type {dash} {dash}'

[07:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'raw right at the end. Or, of course, find raw in your settings here. Already, you can start to see a difference. Then when it comes to stylize, you have two options. You can either decrease it a little or increase it a little.'

[08:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Not a lot, just a little. I think 200 is the max. Honestly, I like to stick to around 185. After all of my testing, that\'s my sweet spot, but you can do whatever you want. I think your other'

[08:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'realistic option is to lower the stylize a little bit, maybe anywhere between like 50 and 80. And that becomes more important when you\'re writing longer prompts and you\'re noticing that'

[08:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Midjourney isn\'t listening to you. Like if I ask for something silly like an origami watercolor oil painting of Margot Robbie, I think lowering the stylize value a little bit is going to help you out. But you also have to throw'

[08:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some chaos into your prompt. Now, by default, Midjourney version eight is better at providing variety. However, we can always increase that a little bit. I\'d say anywhere from like six to 13, maybe. Here it is with six. Nine is'

[09:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'probably my favorite value, and then we have 13 here. You can go higher, for sure, but you really don\'t know what you\'re getting yourself into. And the last parameter you want to add to your prompt is EXP. I\'m pretty sure this just'

[09:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stands for experimental. It cannot be found in your settings. You actually have to type it in your prompt. And again, you don\'t want to go too high with this. Maybe 15 being the limit, somewhere between eight and 15. That\'s'

